ABSTRACT

This dissertation establishes a unified mathematical and computational framework for the design of extreme-scale extraterrestrial infrastructure. We propose Anti-Entropic Design (AED) , a methodology that encodes physical laws as categorical structures and design objectives as information-geometric optimization on a manifold of physically feasible designs. Unlike traditional black-box optimization, AED ensures physical validity by construction through physics-constrained generative models with differentiable constraint enforcement.

The theoretical contribution consists of three pillars: (1) a category-theoretic formulation of multi-physics coupling where conservation laws define composition constraints, formalized via operadic wiring diagrams that make explicit how subsystems interconnect; (2) an information-geometric optimization algorithm that follows natural gradients on the statistical manifold of designs, accounting for epistemic uncertainty and providing fundamental limits via the Cramér–Rao bound; and (3) a fixed-point convergence proof for a multi-fidelity simulation bridge based on contractive neural discrepancy models with a priori Lipschitz bounds.

The engineering application validates this framework through the detailed design of Project Slingstone, a lunar electromagnetic mass driver capable of launching 1000 kg payloads at 2.5 km/s. Using AED, we demonstrate that design-space exploration reduces high-fidelity simulations by over 90% compared to standard Bayesian optimization, while achieving a 9.5% improvement in exit velocity and 13% improvement in efficiency over baseline human designs. Ablation studies isolate the contributions of each framework component: natural gradients account for 4% of the performance gain, the physics-informed representation contributes 3%, and the contractive multi-fidelity bridge enables the 90% simulation reduction. All designs are verified through multi-fidelity numerical simulation, with rigorous handling of lunar-specific constraints including the 14-day night power blackout, radiative cooling in vacuum, and dust abrasion on superconducting tapes.

This work bridges formal mathematical verification with practical systems engineering, providing a scalable paradigm for autonomous infrastructure development in cislunar space. The framework generalizes to other domains including fusion reactor design, hypersonic vehicles, and seismic-optimized civil infrastructure.

